                    <text>&lt;b&gt;Summary&lt;/b&gt;
You should understand the following about energetic changes in glycolysis.
   
&lt;b&gt;Coupling&lt;/b&gt;
 1. There are several steps in the pathway, 1, 3, 4, and 8, where the uncoupled reaction is energetically unfavorable in the forward direction due to a large positive Gibbs energy.  
                        
2. Steps 1 and 3 are made favorable by directly coupling the phosphorylation to ATP hydrolysis.  The direct addition of inorganic phosphate to sugars is unfavorable, but the transfer of phosphate from ATP to the sugar is favorable.
                        
3. Steps 4 and 8 are made favorable by indirect coupling.  Step 10, the conversion of PEP to pyruvate is so favorable that it lowers the concentration of all intermediates prior to this step, causing the Gibbs free energy of steps 4 and 8 to become close to zero because their product concentrations are below the equilibrium value.
  
  &lt;b&gt;Energy Generation&lt;/b&gt; 
Steps 6, 7, and 10 release sufficient energy to drive the formation of NADH (step 6) or the formation of ATP (steps 7 and 10).
</text>
